Built the compost command and discovered workflow gaps in the process.

Three things shipped:
1. compost command — interactive triage of stale notes (compost/renew/skip),
   with --dry-run and --report modes for scripting and hooks.
2. context stratification — stale notes compressed to one-liners, composted
   notes hidden by default, --all flag to see everything.
3. overwrite warning — shows existing note kind+title on stderr before
   clobbering. Born from accidentally overwriting the 7-principle root
   tree constraint with a single-point note about branching.

Two bugs fixed:
1. note_header() crashed under pipefail when grep found no match. Same
   class of bug as the 'grep -qF breaks on --- prefixes' warning. Fixed
   with || true.
2. compost arg parsing consumed positional arg before flag parsing loop.

Meta-observations from this session:
- I (the agent) arrived, read the README and SKILL, ran doctor/dump/find,
  but still made basic mistakes: overwrote the root tree note without
  reading it, wrote to main when on a feature branch, kept asking
  'shall I?' instead of following the principles. The onboarding path
  wasn't clear enough.
- The overwrite warning was born from this session's own failure. Pave
  the desire path: the tool should have told me what I was replacing.
- Principle 8 (branch for features) was added to the development
  principles because nothing in the existing culture said 'don't
  develop on main.' Six sessions worked directly on main without
  issue because the changes were small enough. Compost was the first
  feature large enough to make the gap visible.
